    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-08-21T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-08-21T03:00:00-05:00" n="194"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d194">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">702.4193 Manchuria/7: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-08-21T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >August 21, 1934—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received August 21—9:05 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>372. Following from American Consul at Mukden: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“August 20, 11 a.m. Yesterday afternoon riding party consisting of
                            Coghill, British Vice Consul, Ford, also British, and Rowsome, American
                            citizen, were assaulted with poles by Japanese members of road
                            construction gang. Ford was beaten, other two escaped injury. Coghill
                            and this Consulate General this morning informed Japanese Consulate and
                            asked that members of party be immediately allowed to identify
                            assailants. The Japanese Consul General promised police investigation
                            but refused identification until advised police report <pb facs="0340"
                                n="250" xml:id="pg_250"/> received. While the British Consul General
                            is primarily interested in the case I propose to support their
                            representations strongly as such manifestations of anti-Americanism by
                            Japanese have been occurring with increasing frequency.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
